HEADWORD: Gnomical
<hw>Gnom"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
}</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, fr. <?/: cf. F.
<ets>gnomique</ets>. See <er>Gnome</er> maxim.]</ety> <def>Sententious;
uttering or containing maxims, or striking detached thoughts;
aphoristic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A city long famous as the seat of elegiac and <qex>gnomic</qex>
poetry.</q> <rj><qau>G. R. Lewes.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Gnomic Poets</b></col>, <cd>Greek poets, as Theognis and
Solon, of the sixth century <sc>B. C.</sc>, whose writings consist of
short sententious precepts and reflections.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gnomical</ent>⟦br⟧

